<section xml:id="Electric-Potential-of-Point-Charge"><title> Electric Potential of Point Charge </title>
	<introduction>
		<p>
			Electric potential of a point charge is the building block for electric potential by more complex charge distributions as we will see in the next section.
		</p>

		<sidebyside widths="60% 10% 25% 5%">
			<p> 
				Electric potential of a point charge <m>q</m> located at the origin has the same value at a distance <m>r</m> from it, regardless of the direction.
				<men xml:id="eq-electric-potential-point-charge-restate">
					\phi = \dfrac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_0}\,\dfrac{q}{r}.
				</men>		
			</p>
	 		<p></p>
 

			<image source="./images/electric-potential/e-potential-example-formulas-point-charge.png" width="70%"/>
 
			<p></p>
		</sidebyside>
		<p>
			<!-- This equation is the building block for electric potential by more complex charge distributions as we will see in the next section. For instance, the net electric potential by a collection of point charges is just an algebraic sum of the potentials of each charge give by Eq. <xref ref="eq-electric-potential-point-charge-restate"/>. In this section, we will focus on one-charge system only. -->
		</p>


	</introduction>
	<section> <title>(Calculus) Derivation of the Formula for Electric Potential for Point Charge</title>
		<p>
			To derive formula in <xref ref="eq-electric-potential-point-charge-restate"/>  from the definition of electric potential given in <xref ref="Electric-Potential-Section"/>, we need to perform an integral from the reference point, which is at <m>r=\infty</m> to the field point P, which is at <m>r=r</m>. The integral is required to obtain work done because the electric force varies along the path. Setting the test charge <m>Q</m> to unity makes the integral equal to the electric potential at P.
			<men>
				\phi_P = - \int_\text{ref}^{P} \vec E \cdot d\vec r.
			</men>
			Since electric field is radial, the dot product with <m>d\vec r</m> gives
			<me>
				\vec E \cdot d\vec r = E\: dr = \frac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_0}\,\frac{q}{r^2}dr,
			</me>
			where I have replaced
			the magitude of electric field <m>E</m> by its formula obtained in previous chapter. 
			With reference at <m>r=\infty</m>, upon doing the integration we get the desired result.
			<md>
				<mrow>\phi_P \amp = - \int_\text{\infty}^{r}\frac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_0}\,\frac{q}{r^2}dr </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = \frac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_0}\,\frac{q}{r}.</mrow>
			</md>
		</p>


