	<exercise xml:id="ex-Electric-Potential-of-a-Proton-at-Atomic-Distances-1"><title> Electric Potential of a Proton at Atomic Distances </title>
		<statement>
			<p>
				(a) What is the electric potential of a proton at a distance of Bohr radius, <m>5.29\times 10^{−11}\text{ m}</m>, from the proton?
			</p>
			<p>
				(b) 
				What is the potential energy of an electron when placed <m>5.29\times 10^{−11}\text{ m}</m> from a proton? State both in <m>\text{eV}</m> and <m>\text{J}</m>.
			</p>
			<p>
				(c) What is the electric potential of an electron at a distance of Bohr radius, <m>5.29\times 10^{−11}\text{ m}</m>, from the electron?
			</p>

			<p>
				Data: <m>e = 1.60\times10^{-19}\text{ C}</m>.
			</p>
		</statement>
		<hint> <p> (a) Use <m>\phi</m> for a point charge, (b) <m> Q\times \phi</m> gives potential energu of <m>Q</m>, (c) No additional work required, just the sign needs to be right.  </p> </hint>
		<answer> <p>(a) <m> 27.2\text{ V}</m>, (b) <m>-27.2\text{ eV}</m>, <m> -4.35 \times 10^{-18}\text{ J}</m>, (c) <m>- 27.2\text{ V}</m>.  </p> </answer>
		<solution> <title>(a)</title>
			<p>
				(a)
				Using the electric potential formula for a point charge we get
				<md>
					<mrow> \phi \amp = \dfrac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_0}\,\dfrac{e}{r},</mrow>
					<mrow> \amp = 9\times 10^9\,\dfrac{1.60\times10^{-19}}{ 5.29\times 10^{−11}} </mrow>
					<mrow> \amp = 27.2\text{ V}. </mrow>
				</md>
			</p>
		</solution>
		<solution> <title>(b)</title>
 			<p>
				(b)
				By multiplying potential at the location of the electron by the charge of the electron we will get the potential energy of the electeron.
				<md>
					<mrow> \text{EPE} \amp = -e\,\phi = -27.2\text{ eV},</mrow>
					<mrow> \amp = -1.60\times10^{-19}\text{C}\times 27.2\text{ V}  = -4.35 \times 10^{-18}\text{ J}. </mrow>
				</md>
			</p>
		</solution>
		<solution> <title>(c)</title>
			<p>
				(c)
				This requires no additional work since absolute value of the charge of an electron is same as that of proton. The only difference from (a) is the sign.
				<me>
					\phi = - 27.2\text{ V}.
				</me> 
			</p>
		</solution>



	</exercise>


